        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough Kent</placeName>
                    <date>May 20<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Forchhammer</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>I ought to have written sooner to have thanked you very sincerely for your letter of the 27<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> of April: it told me quite fully &amp; most clearly, all that I wanted to know of your Geology.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Prof. Steenstrup’s specimen which I owe first to your kindness have been of <hi rend="underline">great</hi> use &amp; interest to me: I have now described 33 fossil Pedunculated Cirripides, &amp; they are in M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Sowerby’s hands to make drawings of.—</p>
<p>With my very sincere thanks | Believe me | Yours very truly | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The letter has not been found. The geological information may have been in answer to <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1317.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. J. S. Steenstrup, 3 April [1850]</ref>, asking about the relationship of the chalk formations of Scania, Faxoe, and Westphalia. In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2621.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Fossil Cirripedia</hi> (1851): </ref>7, CD cited Forchhammer and Steenstrup as his authorities for considering them equivalent formations, more recent than the common Upper or White Chalk and equivalent to the formation of Maastricht.</note>
        </div>        
            
